<br>
windows 95 and 98 were built on top of dos.  windows nt, 2000, and xp have absolutly nothing to do with dos.  they can emulate a dos shell within a command prompt window, but there is no 'real' dos behind it.  <br>
if you do not have a floppy drive, you can try to burn a win98 boot disk onto a cd and boot from that.  it may or may not work, depending on your system.  another option is to set up your system as dual bootable.  create a new disk partition on your hard drive (using partition magic or similar utility) and Install dos or win 98 on the second partition.  you can have an option of which os you want to boot to when you turn on the computer.  <br>
finally, you can install the windows 2000 recovery console.  this gives you command line controll of the system.  the commands are in windows help.<br>
<br>
instalation instructions pasted from window help:<br>
To install the Recovery Console as a startup option<br>
<br>
With Windows running, insert the Windows 2000 Professional CD into your CD-ROM drive. <br>
Click No when prompted to upgrade to Windows 2000. <br>
At the command prompt, switch to your CD-ROM drive, and then type the following: <br>
\i386\winnt32.exe /cmdcons<br>
<br>
Follow the instructions on the screen. <br>
 Notes<br>
<br>
To run the Recovery Console, you must restart your computer and select the Recovery Console option from the list of available operating systems. <br>
You must be logged on as an administrator or a member of the Administrators group in order to complete this procedure. If your computer is connected to a network, network policy settings may also prevent you from completing this procedure. <br>
To see the commands available on the Recovery Console, type help at the command prompt. <br>
You can allow a user to run the Recovery Console without logging on by enabling the Automatic administrative logon when using recovery console attribute in the Group Policy snap-in. This attribute is located in the console tree under Local Computer Policy/Computer Configuration/Windows Settings/Security Settings/Local Policies/Security Options. <br>
If your computer will not start, you can run the Recovery Console from the Windows 2000 Professional CD (if you have a bootable CD-ROM drive) or the Setup disks. See Related Topics for information on running the Recovery Console when your computer will not start. <br>
